recordings.loc: Lucky Hammock, Homestead, Miami-Dade County, Florida

recordings.rmk: Fol XC323786 Continuation of dawn song/ same male. Closer Am Robin now singing dawn song. Interestingly, pre-dawn AMRO singers were limited to areas east of the parkway.

Fol XC323781 Sixth recording in series of this and E Kingbird giving dawn song simultaneously from same large river birch. Still closer to E Kingbird at this point. Characteristics data regarding S-t Fly song.
Fol XC323758 Same bird and E Kingbird perched giving dawn song. Northern Cardinal, American Robin (probably also vocalizing earlier), and Red--winged Blackbird now joining in dawn chorus.

Same as "pre-dawn" song. Bird was singing ~1 hour before dawn before recording taken. Given by male perched at top of large river birch near parking lot. Male Eastern Kingbird also giving dawn song closely perched in same tree. Numerous Purple Martin Circling overhead. The few calls between song in cut possibly should be listed as portion of song rather than calls? Scissor-tailed Fly locally will sometimes begin singing for extensive bouts at any time after 10 pm or so, then frequently by 0415-0430 in mornings. Distant S-t Flycatcher also giving dawn song. Distant E Kingbird giving dawn song and calls. Characteristics data regarding song.
Recorded from a perch on a telephone wire approx 25ft from ground, approx 25ft away. Edited to remove background noise and edited for length.

Fol XC323788 First call at :06 Male Scissor-tailed Fly now stops song, begins calling only as light grows, then relocates. Eastern Kingbird continues on with dawn song for a short while into increasing light. Typical behavior for both species. Volume increased during/while recording
Fol XC323784 Continuation of dawn song/ same male.
Fol XC323774 Still closer to E Kingbird during this cut
Fol XC323754 Same bird and E Kingbird perched giving dawn song. Another distant Scissor-tailed Fly and E Kingbird also giving dawn song in background. Loud Northern Mockingbird in foreground.

Response to playback of dawn song from a pair (same as in XC179044) from crown of Celtis trees in coastal chenier habitat. A Mimus polyglottos was perched immediately below the Tyrannus, singing for much of the cut. Bouts of playback were edited from the cut.

Vocalizations from a pair perched in tops of small Celtis (5-6m up) in response to playback of scold tape. "Kik" and quiet gravelly notes are from the Tyrannus. The higher "peek!" is Empidonax virescens.
